, palmate isochelae. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, C, 700 µm; D, F-J, 10 µm; E, 5 µm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,647,1494,1704]" box="[113,193,1494,1520]" pageId="3" pageNumber="372">
<emphasis box="[113,193,1494,1520]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="372">Spicules</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[113,647,1494,1704]" lastBlockId="3.[677,1210,1279,1704]" pageId="3" pageNumber="372">
Oxeote-styles almost smooth, straight or gently curved and seldom malformed (
<figureCitation box="[474,563,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[114,125,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[114,1211,194,1213]" captionTargetId="figure-265@4.[133,1194,194,1152]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 3. — Iophon terranovae n. sp.; A, oxeote-styles; B, tylote; C, slender style; D, palmate anisochelae; E, oxeote-style ends; F, bipocilla. Scale bars: A-C, 100 µm; D-F, 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757723" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757723/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="372">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
). Their basal extremity bears typically a mucron which can be straight or hooked, bifid or almost inconspicuous (
<figureCitation box="[223,339,1647,1673]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="3.[113,124,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[174,1166,203,1146]" captionTargetId="figure-4@3.[161,1180,190,1160]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIG. 2. — Iophon terranovae n. sp.; A, paratype; B, C, thick ectosomal layer of vertically arranged acanthostyles (arrow) supported by the choanosomal reticulation; D, E, unequal ended bipocilla; F, G, bifid and hooked extremities of acanthostyles; H-J, palmate isochelae. Scale bars: A, 1 cm; B, C, 700 µm; D, F-J, 10 µm; E, 5 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757719" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757719/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="372">Figs 2F, G</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[352,386,1647,1673]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[114,125,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[114,1211,194,1213]" captionTargetId="figure-265@4.[133,1194,194,1152]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 3. — Iophon terranovae n. sp.; A, oxeote-styles; B, tylote; C, slender style; D, palmate anisochelae; E, oxeote-style ends; F, bipocilla. Scale bars: A-C, 100 µm; D-F, 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757723" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757723/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="372">3E</figureCitation>
). The other end is alike or more or less acerate. The presence of a sub- terminal swelling is frequent and short, polytylote forms are not rare (
<figureCitation box="[947,1036,1310,1336]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[114,125,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[114,1211,194,1213]" captionTargetId="figure-265@4.[133,1194,194,1152]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 3. — Iophon terranovae n. sp.; A, oxeote-styles; B, tylote; C, slender style; D, palmate anisochelae; E, oxeote-style ends; F, bipocilla. Scale bars: A-C, 100 µm; D-F, 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757723" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757723/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="372">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
). The swellings may be finely spined and the terminal part of the styles may be seldom rugose. Single spines may be found at the basal end of the acanthostyles which measure 200-580 (431) × 18-24 (22) µm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[677,1210,1279,1704]" pageId="3" pageNumber="372">
Slender styles, straight or curved, with a small, single spine on the head (
<figureCitation box="[986,1081,1525,1551]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="4.[114,125,1175,1192]" captionTargetBox="[114,1211,194,1213]" captionTargetId="figure-265@4.[133,1194,194,1152]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIG. 3. — Iophon terranovae n. sp.; A, oxeote-styles; B, tylote; C, slender style; D, palmate anisochelae; E, oxeote-style ends; F, bipocilla. Scale bars: A-C, 100 µm; D-F, 100 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5757723" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5757723/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="372">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). They are rather numerous in the choanosome but almost absent in the ectosome. They are 375-540 (440) µm long and not more than 4-5 µm thick. They are generally considered to be juvenile spicules (Topsent 1907).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[111,128,234,259]" box="[111,128,234,259]" pageId="4" pageNumber="373">A</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="373">B C E F D</paragraph>
